It seems to me that the separation of the two vesicles is almost completed at the moment of the constriction of the whole. In the stages of Pluteus, in which an age of six days has been reached, the digestive tract is well developed and rather complicated, its different regions being sharply distinguished. The entrance to the mouth presents a wide, slightly depressed space, Pl. V, fig). 82-83 m, well limited by high columnar cells and extending over a good deal of the anterior ventral concave area of the larva. Posteriorly the mouth nar- rows into the oesophagus, fig). 82—83 oe, which is a rather long thick- walled tube, lined with a high ciliated columnar epithelium‚ round which fine contr-actile fibres are to be observed, the oesophagus thus acquiring the capability of powerful contraction. But the oesophagus is also able to shorten, and in such a state it presents rather a spacious cavity.
